Degrees of E₈: [2, 8, 12, 14, 18, 20, 24, 30]
  Contains KEY₁=2 and h=30
  Contains h(E₇)=18 and |BT|=24
  Contains h(F₄)=h(E₆)=12
  Contains rank(E₈)=8 and dim(G₂)=14

E₈ degrees and their (2,3,5) decomposition:
    2 = 2
    8 = 2·2·2
   12 = 2·2·3
   14 = 2·7
   18 = 2·3·3
   20 = 2·2·5
   24 = 2·2·2·3
   30 = 2·3·5

ALL E₈ degrees factor into {2, 3, 5, 7} only!
And 7 = KEY₁² + KEY₂ = 2² + 3
So E₈ degrees factor into {KEY₁, KEY₂, KEY₁+KEY₂, KEY₁²+KEY₂}

======================================================================
PART 6: THE DEGREE-TOURNAMENT CONNECTION
======================================================================

E₈ degrees as tournament data:
    2: KEY₁, det(E₇)
    8: rank(E₈), KEY₁³
   12: h(E₆)=h(F₄), KEY₁²·KEY₂
   14: dim(G₂), KEY₁·(KEY₁²+KEY₂)
   18: h(E₇), KEY₁·KEY₂²
   20: KEY₁²·(KEY₁+KEY₂), = 4·5
   24: |BT|, KEY₁³·KEY₂
   30: h(E₈), KEY₁·KEY₂·(KEY₁+KEY₂)

Product of degrees = |W(E₈)| = 696729600
  = 696729600
  = 2^14 · 3^5 · 5^2 · 7^1

  |W(E₈)| = 2^14 · 3^5 · 5^2 · 7
  = KEY₁^14 · KEY₂^5 · (KEY₁+KEY₂)^2 · (KEY₁²+KEY₂)
  Exponents: [14, 5, 2, 1] — sum = 22

Weyl group orders factored into tournament primes:
  |W(G₂)| = 12 = 2^2·3
  |W(F₄)| = 1152 = 2^7·3^2
  |W(E₆)| = 51840 = 2^7·3^4·5
  |W(E₇)| = 2903040 = 2^10·3^4·5·7
  |W(E₈)| = 696729600 = 2^14·3^5·5^2·7

======================================================================
PART 7: EXPONENT GAPS AND THE TOURNAMENT RECURRENCE
======================================================================

Exponent gaps (differences between consecutive exponents):
  G₂: [1, 5]
    Gaps: [4]
  F₄: [1, 5, 7, 11]
    Gaps: [4, 2, 4]
  E₆: [1, 4, 5, 7, 8, 11]
    Gaps: [3, 1, 2, 1, 3]
  E₇: [1, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 17]
    Gaps: [4, 2, 2, 2, 2, 4]
  E₈: [1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29]
    Gaps: [6, 4, 2, 4, 2, 4, 6]

E₈ exponent gaps: [6, 4, 2, 4, 2, 4, 6]
  Palindromic! (from exponent duality)
  Contains only {2, 4, 6} = {KEY₁, KEY₁², KEY₁·KEY₂}
  All gaps are EVEN — because exponents are all odd!

E₇ exponent gaps: [4, 2, 2, 2, 2, 4]
  Palindromic!
  Contains only {2, 4} = {KEY₁, KEY₁²}
  E₇ is 'simpler' than E₈ in gap structure

E₆ exponent gaps: [3, 1, 2, 1, 3]
  Palindromic!
  Contains {1, 2, 3} = {unit, KEY₁, KEY₂}
  The ONLY exceptional with non-even gaps
  (because E₆ has both even and odd exponents)

GAS STRUCTURE MIRRORS DYNKIN DIAGRAMS:
  E₈: all even gaps → simply-laced, all exponents odd
  E₇: all even gaps → simply-laced, all exponents odd
  E₆: mixed gaps → has BOTH even and odd exponents
  This is because E₆ is the only E-type with det ≠ 1
  det(E₆) = 3 = KEY₂ — introduces parity mixing

